{East's 2\C cue-bid shows a limit-raise or better in \Ss. West is to play 4\S. North leads the \C2. South plays the \CK.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=2  \D=1  \C=1  Total = 4

You have one loser too many. If North holds either the \HA or the \DK this will be an easy contract, but South opened the bidding so he probably has most of the high cards. It does look like North holds the \CQ based on his low lead and South's play to trick one.

Having gone through that thought process what is your Plan?

You will need to discard a loser on dummy's fourth \D, but you must do so without ever letting North gain the lead since North is the defender who can lead through dummy's \HK. And the only card that North can get the lead with is the \CQ.

Hold-ups are usually used in notrump hands, but here you use one to prevent the Danger Hand from gaining the lead. Let South have the \CK. He cannot play a red card without helping you so he will surely play another \C. 

Pull trumps in two rounds. Then play the \DT and let it ride.

South will win this but he is helpless. Whatever he plays you will be able to discard a \H loser on dummy's \D.

If you had taken the first \C trick South would have won your later \D finesse, put his partner on lead with the \CQ and then swallowed up your \HK.

Of course if North had been clever enough to lead a \H originally this Deal wouldn't be here.}
